[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, integration depth across specialists and external systems, and care-team backstop intensity)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria is 68. Maria has Type 2 diabetes (managed, A1c around 7.2), hypertension (managed, on lisinopril), atrial fibrillation (anticoagulated on apixaban), and was diagnosed three months ago with stage II colon cancer after a screening colonoscopy turned up a mass. Maria is post-op from a partial colectomy six weeks ago, has just started adjuvant chemotherapy at the hospital's cancer center, sees a cardiologist for the AFib, sees an endocrinologist for the diabetes, sees a primary care physician at a different practice that is in-network for her Medicare Advantage plan, sees an oncologist at the cancer center, and has just been referred to a registered dietitian for nutrition support during chemotherapy. Maria has a daughter who lives forty minutes away and helps with appointments when she can. Maria has Medicare plus a Medicare Advantage plan, which has its own care-management team that has called Maria twice. The hospital system has its own care-coordinator (an RN) assigned to Maria as part of the oncology program. The PCP's office has a care-coordinator (a medical assistant) who follows up on referrals. None of these care-coordinators talk to each other.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria, on a typical Tuesday at 10:14 AM, is sitting at her kitchen table holding a manila folder full of paper. The folder has: the discharge instructions from her colectomy, which mention a follow-up with the surgeon at six weeks (Maria has not scheduled this), a follow-up with the oncologist (scheduled, last week), and a referral to a colorectal surveillance program (Maria has not heard anything). The folder has a chemotherapy treatment summary that lists each cycle, when to call about side effects, what symptoms warrant the ED, and a phone number Maria has called twice and left voicemail at. The folder has a printout from the cardiologist with instructions about pausing apixaban two days before any procedure, which Maria's surgeon also told her, and which the oncologist asked Maria about last week with a slightly worried expression. The folder has a fax cover sheet from the PCP's office with the name of the dietitian Maria was supposed to be referred to, with no phone number, no address, no instructions about whether the referral has been sent or whether Maria should call. The folder has a Medicare Advantage explanation-of-benefits with a denied claim for an outpatient lab Maria does not remember getting. The folder has a yellow sticky note in Maria's handwriting that says "ask oncologist about glucose since chemo started" and another that says "call about port site, it's red?". Maria has a phone on the table. Maria does not know who to call first.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is what care coordination, in 2026, looks like for a meaningful fraction of complex patients with multiple chronic conditions plus an acute episode of care: it is the patient's job. The patient (or their family caregiver, when there is one) is the integrator. The patient holds the folder. The patient remembers the medication interactions. The patient catches the missing referrals. The patient calls the oncologist about the port site. The patient is, in operations terms, the message bus. When the patient is well-resourced (educated, English-speaking, with a family caregiver who has time, with health literacy, with their own electronic health-records portal access, with the patience and persistence to make twelve phone calls), the system mostly works. When the patient is not (limited English, no caregiver, low health literacy, multiple competing demands, cognitive load from the disease itself), the system fails, often silently, and the failure shows up months later as a missed surveillance imaging study, a worsening untreated condition, an avoidable readmission, an avoidable ED visit, or (in the worst cases) a missed cancer recurrence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The numbers, in the U.S. healthcare system, are not subtle. A meaningful fraction of patients in the Medicare population have multiple chronic conditions; among older adults, the proportion with two or more chronic conditions is the majority. <!-- TODO: verify; the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services and the Centers for Disease Control publish data on chronic-condition prevalence in the Medicare population; specific figures vary by year and definition --> Patients with multiple chronic conditions account for a disproportionate share of healthcare spending, hospitalizations, and ED visits. <!-- TODO: verify; CMS data on multi-chronic-condition cost concentration is published annually; specific figures vary --> Care fragmentation across providers is associated with higher costs, more hospitalizations, more ED visits, more medication-related adverse events, and worse patient-reported outcomes. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on care-fragmentation outcomes is extensive; specific findings vary by population and metric --> Care-coordination interventions have evidence of effect on some of these metrics, with the strongest evidence for nurse-led care management in high-risk populations. <!-- TODO: verify; nurse-led care management has documented effect on hospitalization rates, ED-visit rates, and patient-reported outcomes in high-risk populations; specific effect sizes vary --> The supply of trained care-coordination staff (RNs in particular, plus social workers, plus pharmacists, plus community-health workers) is structurally constrained, more so since 2020. <!-- TODO: verify; nursing-workforce shortages and care-management staffing constraints have been documented by HRSA, CMS, and industry reports; specific figures vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of digital tools in this space tried, and mostly failed, to address this. The first wave was patient portals, which gave patients access to some of their own data but did almost nothing for cross-system coordination. The second wave was care-management software for the care-coordinators themselves: case-load tracking, task lists, telephonic outreach support. The clinical-content side was the strongest of the three waves, but the patient-facing side stayed limited. The third wave, beginning around 2018, was patient-facing care-coordination apps from health systems and from payers, which usually presented appointments, medications, and care-plan tasks in a list, with reminders. Patients used these apps to varying degrees; the operational gain was real but bounded. None of these waves materially closed the integration-across-providers gap, because the gap is not a UI problem; it is a "the systems do not talk to each other and a human has to be the integrator" problem. The patient was that human. The care-coordinator (where one existed) was sometimes that human. In neither case was the human equipped with the time, the data, or the workflow to do the integration well.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changes the workflow shape is the arrival of large language models that can carry on a coherent, multi-turn, contextually-aware conversation across a patient's full care landscape, do tool calls into the institution's scheduling, referral, EHR, payer-eligibility, and benefits systems, surface specific actionable next steps grounded in the patient's actual care plan and active referrals, and bridge to a human care-coordinator when the situation needs one. The bot is not a care-coordinator. The bot is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the patient (or the family caregiver) get to the right next action in their care journey, with tight integration to the care-coordinator workforce that handles the cases that need human judgment. The bot's primary value is not in the clinical content (other recipes in this chapter cover that better) but in the cross-system orchestration: the bot has the patient's referrals, the appointment calendar, the medication list, the active care plan, the open follow-up items, and the benefits posture in working memory simultaneously, and it can answer questions and take action across all of them in a single conversation, without the patient having to call seven offices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that helps complex patients (typically multi-condition, multi-provider, often with active acute or post-acute episodes layered on top of chronic-condition management) navigate their care across providers, track their referrals, manage their care transitions, and surface the next right action when one of the threads is dropping. It does this with explicit integration to the institution's care-coordinator workforce and to the care-management programs the patient is enrolled in.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a care-coordinator. The bot does not replace the RN care-coordinator. The bot does not provide nurse-level clinical judgment. The bot does not do prior authorizations on behalf of the patient. The bot does not negotiate with payers. The bot does not deliver care-management interventions that require a licensed clinician. The bot is, structurally and explicitly, a tool that surfaces actionable next steps and bridges to humans for everything beyond that surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a replacement for the patient's primary care physician or specialty providers. The bot does not provide medical advice that should come from the patient's clinicians. The bot does not change medications. The bot does not interpret test results. The bot does not handle clinical questions outside of routing-and-information surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not the same product as the chronic-disease coach (recipe 11.7). The chronic-disease coach is condition-specific behavior change for a single condition. The care-coordination assistant is multi-condition orchestration across providers and across systems. Patients with both deployments may have both bots; the bots share consent-gated context but have distinct scopes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-size-fits-all product. The needs of a high-utilizer patient with multiple chronic conditions and active cancer treatment are very different from the needs of a previously-healthy patient with a new diagnosis recovering from a single procedure. The institutional deployment typically targets a specific population segment (patients in care-management programs, patients with documented multi-condition burden, patients in active oncology or transplant or organ-failure care, post-acute-discharge patients in their first 30-90 days, and similar high-coordination-need cohorts).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The integration work to wire the bot into scheduling, referral management, EHR, payer-eligibility, benefits, care-management workflow, and the institution's care-coordinator queue is multi-quarter. The clinical-content investment is multi-quarter. The care-coordinator workforce-coordination work is multi-quarter. Institutions building this expecting a fast time-to-value are usually disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is concentrated in three places: cross-system orchestration the patient cannot easily do on their own (the bot has the referrals and the appointment calendar and the medication list in working memory at once), low-friction next-step surfacing for the patient (the bot answers "who do I call about X" and, when permitted, just calls or schedules), and warm handoff to the care-coordinator workforce for the cases that need human judgment. A bot evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. A bot evaluated on referral-completion rate, appointment-attendance rate, care-transition-quality metrics (30-day readmission, 30-day ED revisit, time-to-post-discharge follow-up), patient-reported coordination experience, and care-coordinator workload offload is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Care Coordination Across Systems and Providers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Software, and Why The Latest Attempts Are Different
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-paper-folder problem for almost all of its history. The reason is structural. The U.S. healthcare system is not a single system; it is a collection of organizational silos (health systems, independent practices, ambulatory surgery centers, imaging centers, pharmacy networks, lab vendors, payer organizations, durable-medical-equipment vendors, home-health agencies, post-acute facilities, community-based organizations) that do not share a common data layer, do not share a common care plan, do not share a common identifier for the patient (despite decades of effort), and do not share a common communication standard. Inside each silo, the workflow is reasonably integrated. Across silos, integration is bilateral, manual, faxed, phoned, and frequently broken. The patient is the cross-silo bus.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The data-interoperability story has improved meaningfully over the past decade. FHIR APIs are increasingly available at health systems, ONC interoperability rules have pushed information-blocking remediation, TEFCA is operational for cross-network exchange, and many institutions have invested in care-management platforms that integrate with their EHR. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA (Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement) became operational in late 2023 and continues to expand; ONC information-blocking rules have been progressively enforced since 2021 --> The integration is uneven; the silos are not gone; but the data is more accessible than it was a decade ago. The bot's value depends on this incremental progress; without FHIR access to the patient's chart, without API access to the institution's scheduling system, without API access to the referral-management system, without payer-eligibility integration, the bot can do little beyond what the patient could do alone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changes the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can do tool calls into the systems that hold the patient's care landscape, can hold the cross-system context in working memory, can converse fluidly with the patient about their care across providers, and can take action (within the institution's authorization scope) on the patient's behalf. The earlier waves of care-coordination software lacked all of these capabilities; the bot does not just present a list of tasks to the patient but actually orchestrates across systems, with the patient's authenticated session driving the authorization scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "task list the patient checks" to "conversational orchestrator that integrates across systems and takes action where authorized." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: cross-system orchestration (the bot has the referrals and the appointment calendar and the medication list and the care plan in working memory simultaneously, where the patient holding a folder has them as separate paper artifacts), low-friction next-step surfacing (the bot answers "who do I call" and, when permitted, just calls or schedules), and warm handoff to the care-coordinator workforce (the bot bridges to a human RN-or-equivalent for the cases that need clinical judgment, with the conversation context attached).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what care coordination is and is not, because the term is used differently in different parts of the industry. Care coordination, as used in this recipe, refers to the operational and administrative work of integrating a patient's care across providers and across systems: tracking referrals, scheduling and rescheduling appointments, surfacing the patient's care plan to the patient, reconciling medications across prescribers, navigating benefits, supporting transitions of care, surfacing open follow-up items, and connecting the patient to the right human resource when the situation calls for one. It does not refer to care management (the broader discipline of clinical case management for high-risk patients, which is RN-led work that includes assessment, care-plan development, intervention, and outcome monitoring), to disease management (the condition-specific behavior-change work covered in recipe 11.7), or to social-care navigation (the related-but-distinct work of connecting patients to community resources for social-determinants concerns, sometimes called community-health-worker outreach). The bot in this recipe touches all three at the boundary; it is the operational-coordination layer that complements them rather than replacing them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (active conditions, current medications, open referrals, scheduled appointments, care plan if one exists, care-management program enrollment, recent encounters, recent test results, recent communications, stated patient preferences, primary-care-team identity, specialty-team identities, family-caregiver authorization where present, payer benefits posture), access to a structured library of cross-system tools (scheduling, referral-tracking, appointment-rescheduling, care-plan retrieval, medication-reconciliation, benefits-lookup, after-visit-summary retrieval, lab-result retrieval where consented, message-routing to clinicians and care-coordinators, transportation-support routing, social-determinants-resource-routing), and a careful set of escalation pathways to the institution's care-coordinator workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is multiple conversation types. Patient-initiated conversations are the most common pattern. Bot-initiated conversations happen on specific triggers: post-discharge windows opening, missed appointments, missed referrals (a referral with no scheduled appointment after a defined window), missed care-plan tasks, lab results requiring follow-up, care-coordinator requests for between-visit check-ins. Care-team-initiated conversations happen when the patient's care-coordinator wants the bot to surface a specific item to the patient (e.g., "remind Maria the surgical follow-up is overdue").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Onboarding and consent.** The patient is enrolled in the care-coordination program by their care-management team or self-enrolls through the institution's portal, with documented consent for the bot to access chart context, referral status, scheduling, benefits, and care-coordinator-workforce integration. The first conversation does the disclosure work: the bot identifies itself as a chat tool, names the human-care-coordinator availability, names the bot's scope (operational coordination, not clinical advice), names the data-access posture, and acknowledges the family-caregiver consent posture if relevant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system context loading.** Every conversation begins with a longitudinal-context refresh: pull the patient's open referrals (with status: ordered, scheduled, completed, no-show, cancelled), the appointment calendar across providers (with status: scheduled, completed, no-show, rescheduled), the medication list (active, recently changed, recently discontinued), the care plan if one exists (with active goals and tasks), the care-management program-enrollment status, recent encounter summaries (last 90 days), recent lab results, recent communications, and the consent posture. The bot has all of this in working memory at the start of the conversation; the patient does not have to recite it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated coordination conversations.** The patient can engage at any time about within-scope topics: appointment scheduling, rescheduling, and reminders; referral status (has the referral been sent, has the receiving practice scheduled the appointment, what should the patient do if they have not heard back); care-plan task surfacing (what is open, when is it due, what does it mean); medication reconciliation questions ("which of these am I supposed to be taking; the cardiologist changed something but the bottle from the pharmacy is the old one"); test-result-related navigation ("I got a lab result that says abnormal; who do I follow up with"); benefits-and-billing navigation ("the EOB says my visit was denied; what do I do"); transitions-of-care navigation (post-discharge follow-up, post-procedure follow-up); transportation-support navigation; and social-determinants-resource navigation when the bot's institutional integration includes those resources.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Bot-initiated check-ins on coordination-failure triggers.** The bot proactively surfaces issues the patient may not have noticed: a referral that has been open for 14 days without a scheduled appointment; a discharge with no scheduled post-discharge follow-up at day 7; a care-plan task that is overdue by 7 days; a lab result that is flagged as requiring follow-up that has not been actioned. The bot-initiated check-ins are bounded in frequency to avoid surveillance flavor; the patient can opt out or adjust intensity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Action-on-behalf-of-the-patient within scope.** When the bot has institutional authorization, it can take action: schedule a recommended appointment, request a refill, send a non-clinical message to the care-coordinator, request a benefits-eligibility check, request a transportation arrangement, request a social-determinants resource referral. The bot does not take clinical action (cannot adjust medications, cannot order tests, cannot complete a referral with clinical content) without a licensed-clinician in the loop.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Warm handoff to the care-coordinator workforce.** The bot escalates to a licensed care-coordinator when the situation calls for it: any clinical question outside the bot's scope, any patient distress that suggests care-management intervention, any sustained-trajectory pattern of missed coordination tasks (a strong leading indicator of social-determinants barriers, cognitive impairment, or care-burden overload), any patient request for a human, any low-confidence handling. The handoff is warm with conversation context attached; the bot stays present until the human has joined.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-provider message routing within scope.** The bot can route patient questions to the right clinician's inbox. A question about the surgical-port site goes to the surgical team, with structured context. A question about chemotherapy side effects goes to the oncology team. A question about the cardiologist's instructions goes to the cardiology team. The routing is based on the institution's directory and the patient's care-team configuration, not freestyled by the LLM.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family-caregiver-authorized conversations.** Where the patient has authorized a family caregiver, the bot can engage with the caregiver within the authorized scope. The caregiver-engagement consent posture, the access scope, and the audit trail are explicit; the bot does not silently let a caregiver substitute for the patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team-facing summary delivery.** The bot generates structured summaries (weekly digests, monthly summaries, alert events for significant issues) for the patient's care-coordinator, the patient's PCP, and (with consent) the patient's specialty teams. The summaries are designed to fit the care-team's existing workflow tooling; they are not a parallel data stream the care team has to learn a new tool to use.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term relationship maintenance, with operational discipline.** The bot maintains conversation history and stated patient preferences. The bot acknowledges prior content where appropriate ("you mentioned last week that scheduling has been hard with your daughter's work travel") in ways that support continuity without simulating friendship. The line is similar to but more permissive than the mental-health bot's; care-coordination conversations do not have the same companion-pattern risk profile, but the discipline is still in place.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, prompt it with "you are a helpful care-coordination assistant," and let it engage with patients about whatever they bring. This breaks in several specific ways.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no access to the cross-system data.** The bot's value is fundamentally in cross-system orchestration. A bot without tool access to scheduling, referrals, EHR, benefits, and care-team-workflow systems cannot do the work. Tool integration is the architectural floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents data when grounding is weak.** A bot responding to "do I have any open referrals" without an actual tool call to the referral system will, in some fraction of cases, fabricate plausible-sounding referrals or miss real ones. The grounded-tool-call discipline is non-negotiable; the bot answers from the system of record, not from parametric memory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no scope discipline about clinical advice.** A bot that drifts into clinical advice ("you should probably take the lower dose; the higher one sounds like too much") is delivering medical advice it should not. The bot's scope is operational and informational, not clinical; the prompt, the output safety, and the sampled review reinforce this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to take action versus when to ask.** A bot that schedules an appointment without confirming with the patient is overstepping; a bot that asks for confirmation on every minor action is overhead. The action-confirmation thresholds are institutional policy; the bot enforces them rather than improvising.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient distress.** A patient who is overwhelmed by the care burden often presents the same as a patient who has a quick scheduling question; the difference matters for whether to handle the conversation in scope or escalate to a care-coordinator. The bot's distress-detection and care-coordinator-handoff thresholds are explicit; the generalist LLM tends to either miss distress or over-escalate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of family-caregiver consent.** A patient may have authorized a family caregiver for some care-coordination tasks but not others; the caregiver may engage with the bot but the bot should know what the caregiver is authorized to see and do. The consent posture is explicit; the generalist LLM does not handle this on its own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of state-specific coordination considerations.** Some states have specific consent rules around adolescent care coordination, around behavioral-health information sharing, around substance-use-treatment information sharing (42 CFR Part 2), around HIV-status information sharing. <!-- TODO: verify; state-specific information-sharing rules including adolescent consent, behavioral-health-information protections, 42 CFR Part 2, HIV-status protections vary by state and are documented in legal guides --> The bot's information surface respects these constraints; the generalist LLM does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of social-determinants signal.** Sustained patterns of missed appointments, missed referrals, and care-plan-task non-completion are often signals of social-determinants barriers (transportation, housing, food, financial barriers, caregiver burden). The bot's routing of these patterns to care-management or to social-care navigation is institutional policy; the generalist LLM does not encode it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to care coordination.** The conversation contains sensitive PHI across multiple providers and possibly across multiple legal entities (the health system, the payer, external practices). The data-handling, the cross-entity access, and the audit posture have to handle each of these explicitly. The model alone does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the care-coordinator workforce capacity.** A bot that escalates everything to the care-coordinator queue overwhelms the workforce; a bot that escalates nothing is an unsafe bot. The escalation thresholds are calibrated to the workforce capacity and to clinical-quality requirements; the generalist LLM does not encode the workforce model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of end-of-care transitions.** Patients sometimes complete a course of acute care and step down to lower-touch coordination; sometimes step up to higher-touch care management; sometimes transition to hospice or palliative care; sometimes are bereaved. The bot's behavior in each of these transitions is institutional policy and is sensitive; the generalist LLM does not handle this gracefully.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Care Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, crisis-screening (still applicable here for any conversation that crosses into mental-health distress), warm-handoff infrastructure. The care-coordination assistant adds six structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system orchestration as architectural primitive.** The bot's value is fundamentally in integrating across systems. The tool surface includes scheduling, referrals, EHR/FHIR, benefits, care-management workflow, transportation, social-determinants resources, and others depending on the institution. Each tool has a versioned schema, an SLA, a fallback-when-unavailable policy, and an audit trail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordinator-workforce integration as primary safety architecture.** Like the mental-health bot's licensed-clinician backstop, the care-coordination assistant has a care-coordinator-workforce backstop. The handoff is warm with full context. The capacity is sized to the population. Under-sized capacity is a deployment-readiness gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family-caregiver-consent posture as explicit architectural element.** Where the patient has authorized a family caregiver, the bot's interactions with the caregiver are scoped, audited, and revocable. The bot does not silently let a caregiver substitute for the patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transitions-of-care discipline as architectural focus.** Care transitions (hospital discharge, skilled-nursing transfer, post-procedure recovery, end-of-treatment, end-of-life transitions) are the highest-risk windows in care coordination. The bot's discipline around transitions includes early proactive engagement (within hours of discharge for post-acute), structured task tracking (post-discharge follow-up at day 7, medication reconciliation at day 3, primary-care follow-up at day 14), aggressive escalation when tasks slip, and graceful handoff at end-of-treatment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants signal escalation as architectural pattern.** Sustained patterns of missed coordination tasks are signals to investigate; the bot routes to social-care navigation, to care-management, or to community-health-worker workflows depending on the institution's configuration. The signal-to-escalation logic is institutionally specified.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-entity data-sharing posture with appropriate governance.** When the bot operates across legal entities (e.g., between a health system and a payer's care-management program), the data-sharing arrangements (BAAs, data-use agreements, permitted-use scope) are explicit. The bot's information surface respects the boundaries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Care Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically hard.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The integration surface is wide.** Scheduling, referrals, EHR/FHIR, benefits, care-management workflow, transportation, social-determinants resources, pharmacy, durable-medical-equipment, home-health, post-acute facilities, community-based organizations. Few institutions have all of these wired up; most have some. The bot's value scales with the integration depth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-entity data sharing is harder than intra-entity.** When the bot needs information from a partner organization (a different health system, an external specialty practice, a payer's care-management program), the BAA-and-data-use-agreement work is multi-quarter. Most institutions deploy the bot intra-entity first and expand to cross-entity over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-coordinator workforce sizing is the dominant operational cost.** As with the mental-health bot, the licensed-or-equivalent workforce cost is typically larger than the AWS infrastructure cost. The bot offloads routine coordination from the care-coordinator queue; the care-coordinator handles the cases that need clinical or operational judgment. Under-investing in the workforce is a deployment-readiness gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome attribution is genuinely hard.** The bot is one of many factors influencing readmission rates, ED-revisit rates, time-to-post-discharge follow-up, and patient-reported coordination experience. The analysis is suggestive rather than causal; matched-cohort or quasi-experimental designs help.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient and caregiver heterogeneity is wide.** A high-functioning English-speaking patient with a family caregiver who has time is a different deployment-target than a limited-English-proficient patient with no caregiver and competing demands. Per-cohort design is non-negotiable; institutions that design for the high-functioning patient and assume the rest will follow are excluding the patients who need the bot most.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Engagement-attrition risk is moderate but specific.** Care-coordination bots have lower engagement-attrition risk than chronic-disease coaching or mental-health support, partly because the use cases are more transactional ("schedule the surgical follow-up") and partly because the patients are usually engaged with their care anyway. The attrition risk concentrates in the populations the bot is most useful for: patients with caregiver burden, patients with cognitive load, patients with low health literacy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are amplified.** Patients with limited English proficiency, patients from cultures where family-caregiver involvement is expected, patients from communities with deep mistrust of the healthcare system, patients with health-literacy gaps. The bot's content is per-language and per-cultural-context, with translations reviewed by behavioral-health-clinical-leadership-equivalent (in this case, by patient-experience and care-management leadership).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The bot's role at end-of-life is sensitive.** Patients on palliative or hospice care have different coordination needs than patients in active curative treatment. The bot's behavior shifts: less aggressive task-prompting, more comfort-care orientation, explicit family-caregiver engagement, graceful conversation-ending, and tight integration with the palliative-care or hospice team. Mishandling this is a reputational and clinical risk.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Bereavement support is out of scope but adjacent.** When a patient dies, the bot's engagement with the family changes. The bot does not silently keep prompting the patient's account; the deceased-status flag changes the bot's behavior to a respectful off-ramp with optional bereavement-resource information. Mishandling this is a reputational risk that has burned several deployments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Adolescent and pediatric considerations are specific.** Adolescent care coordination has consent considerations (the adolescent's confidential health information, the parent's involvement, state-specific adolescent-consent laws). <!-- TODO: verify; adolescent consent in healthcare varies by state and by service type, with specific protections for behavioral-health, substance-use, and reproductive-health services --> Pediatric care coordination is family-centered with the parent or guardian as the primary engaged party. Most adult-deployment products explicitly exclude adolescents; pediatric-specific deployments are designed differently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Older-adult considerations have specific dimensions.** Older adults often have higher coordination needs (more conditions, more providers, more transitions) and, in some cases, less digital comfort. Voice channels, simplified interfaces, family-caregiver engagement, and slow-pace response styles are all per-cohort-specific design choices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disability accessibility is a first-class requirement.** Patients with vision, hearing, motor, or cognitive impairments have specific accessibility needs. The chat widget meets WCAG 2.1 AA; the voice channel supports accessibility-mode; the cognitive-load adaptations are designed in.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The bot's economic case is strongest in capitated and value-based-care contexts.** Fee-for-service economics misalign with care coordination (more coordination means more visits captured, but the bot reduces visit volume in some categories); capitated and value-based-care economics align with care coordination (avoided readmissions, avoided ED visits, improved patient experience all contribute to value-based-care performance). Most deployments live in capitated or value-based contexts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR integration is the dominant technical pattern.** FHIR APIs at health systems have improved meaningfully; institutional EHR vendors have stable FHIR APIs for the common resources (Patient, Encounter, Condition, MedicationStatement, Observation, ServiceRequest for referrals, Appointment, CarePlan, Goal, Communication). <!-- TODO: verify; the major U.S. EHR vendors all support FHIR R4 with varying maturity; specific resource availability varies --> The bot's chart-context loading uses FHIR.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA is operational for cross-network exchange.** Cross-network access to a patient's records (for treatment, payment, and operations purposes) has improved with TEFCA's operational launch. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA became operational in late 2023 with Qualified Health Information Networks (QHINs) onboarding through 2024-2025; specific status varies --> The bot's cross-network data access depends on the institution's TEFCA participation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management platform vendors offer bot-integration patterns.** Mature care-management platforms (with names that change as the market consolidates) offer integration patterns for patient-facing bots. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin-orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for the care-management platform, and integrate with the institution's EHR-and-clinical-workflow infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle care-coordination orchestration well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps naturally to care coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve referrals, retrieve appointments, retrieve medications, retrieve care-plan tasks, retrieve benefits, schedule, message, escalate, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Bot-initiated proactive engagement is calibrated carefully to avoid surveillance flavor.** Mental-health bots default to patient-initiated engagement; care-coordination bots are more permitted to proactively engage on coordination-failure triggers, but the frequency is bounded and the patient can opt out. The calibration is per-population and per-patient-preference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-focused per-cohort monitoring is increasingly an explicit deployment requirement.** Care-coordination interventions have been shown to perform variably across cohorts; institutions deploying bot-mediated coordination are increasingly required (by their clinical-leadership, their compliance-leadership, and in some cases by their accreditation or contract terms) to monitor per-cohort outcomes and to address disparities. <!-- TODO: verify; equity monitoring requirements in care-management programs are reflected in NCQA accreditation standards, CMS quality programs, and institutional clinical-leadership policies; specific requirements vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome metrics for care coordination are well-codified.** Common metrics include 30-day readmission rate, 30-day ED-revisit rate, time-to-post-discharge follow-up, referral-completion rate, appointment-attendance rate, medication-reconciliation-completion rate, patient-reported coordination experience (often via CAHPS or similar instruments), and care-coordinator-workload offload metrics. <!-- TODO: verify; care-coordination outcome metrics are documented in CMS quality programs, NCQA HEDIS measures, and AHRQ care-coordination-measure resources; specific definitions vary --> The bot's evaluation framework draws from these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A healthcare care-coordination assistant decomposes into nine logical stages: enrollment and consent (with family-caregiver-authorization handling), longitudinal-store and cross-system-context initialization, channel entry with disclosure and identity-verification, input safety screening with care-coordination-specific signal detection, identity-and-cross-system-context loading, conversation handling with cross-system-tool-grounded responses, output safety screening with action-confirmation discipline, action execution and warm-handoff routing to care-coordinators when applicable, and audit logging with care-coordination-specific telemetry. The cross-cutting concerns from recipes 11.1 through 11.8 carry forward; this recipe adds the cross-system orchestration, the care-coordinator-workforce integration, the family-caregiver-consent posture, the transitions-of-care discipline, the social-determinants-signal escalation, and the cross-entity data-sharing posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ┌────────── ENROLLMENT + CONSENT ──────────────────────────┐
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m │                                                           │
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m │   [Patient enrolls via institution app, payer portal,     │
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m │    or care-management program referral]                   │
